🧠 1️⃣ age

Definition:
The person’s age (in years).

Why it’s used:
Age is the strongest and most consistent predictor of stroke risk. Arteries stiffen, plaque builds up, and blood pressure rises with age.

Impact:

Risk increases exponentially after age 55.

The older the person, the higher the likelihood of both ischemic and hemorrhagic stroke.

🚻 2️⃣ gender

Definition:
The biological sex of the person (Male/Female/Other).

Why it’s used:
There are biological and lifestyle differences in stroke patterns:

Men tend to have strokes earlier.

Women tend to live longer, so have higher stroke rates in older age.

Impact:

Gender affects hormonal protection, blood pressure trends, and lifestyle exposure (smoking/alcohol).

Often, males have slightly higher predicted risk at younger ages.

❤️ 3️⃣ hypertension

Definition:
Whether the person has chronic high blood pressure (BP ≥ 140/90 mmHg).
Binary variable: 1 = Yes, 0 = No.

Why it’s used:
High BP is the #1 cause of stroke worldwide.

Impact:

Increases risk by 4–6 times.

Damages blood vessel walls → thickening, narrowing, and higher chance of rupture or clot.

💓 4️⃣ heart_disease

Definition:
Whether the person has any cardiovascular condition (like atrial fibrillation, heart failure, etc.).
Binary variable: 1 = Yes, 0 = No.

Why it’s used:
Certain heart problems cause blood clots that can travel to the brain (embolic stroke).

Impact:

Greatly increases stroke probability (especially atrial fibrillation).

Also indicates poor blood circulation or prior cardiovascular strain.

💍 5️⃣ ever_married

Definition:
Whether the person has ever been married (Yes/No).

Why it’s used:
This is not a medical factor — it’s a socio-demographic proxy.

Impact:

In datasets, “Ever Married” tends to correlate with older age, different lifestyle, and stress exposure.

Models may misinterpret it as a risk factor due to its correlation with age, not causation.

💼 6️⃣ work_type

Definition:
Occupation type: Private, Self-employed, Govt_job, Children, or Never_worked.

Why it’s used:
Work type reflects lifestyle patterns, activity level, and stress exposure.

Impact:

Sedentary jobs (office work) and stress-heavy roles correlate with higher stroke risk.

“Children” or “Never worked” categories often imply younger, low-risk individuals.

🏙️ 7️⃣ Residence_type

Definition:
Whether the person lives in an Urban or Rural area.

Why it’s used:
Lifestyle and healthcare access differ between urban and rural populations.

Impact:

Urban → more sedentary lifestyle, fast food, stress → slightly higher risk.

Rural → less healthcare access → higher mortality if stroke occurs.

Impact depends on dataset balance and region.

🍬 8️⃣ avg_glucose_level

Definition:
Average glucose (blood sugar) level in mg/dL.

Why it’s used:
It indicates diabetes or prediabetes, a major stroke risk factor.

Impact:

High glucose → vascular inflammation, plaque buildup, and clot formation.

Each 10 mg/dL increase above normal (≈100 mg/dL) increases stroke risk significantly.

