WORKING:-⚙️ How Each Model Works in Your Stroke Prediction App
Your Flask app takes user input like this 👇
{
  "age": 65,
  "avg_glucose_level": 145,
  "bmi": 30,
  "hypertension": 1,
  "heart_disease": 0,
  "gender": "Male",
  "ever_married": "Yes",
  "work_type": "Private",
  "Residence_type": "Urban",
  "smoking_status": "formerly smoked"
}

Then your backend (ml_utils.py) prepares this data and sends it to 3 trained models — Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoost — to predict the stroke probability.
Here’s what happens behind the scenes 👇

🧩 STEP 1: Preprocessing
Before sending to models:


The data is encoded (Male → 1, Female → 0, etc.)


Missing values are filled.


Numeric values are scaled.


Categorical values are one-hot encoded (converted to binary columns).


This ensures input matches how models were trained.

⚖️ STEP 2: Each Model Predicts
🧠 1️⃣ Logistic Regression


Works like a mathematical formula:
stroke_risk = sigmoid(w1*age + w2*bmi + w3*glucose + ... + b)



It adds all weighted inputs, applies the sigmoid function, and outputs a probability between 0 and 1.


Example:
stroke_risk = 0.35  → means 35% chance of stroke



It’s simple but interpretable — tells you how much each feature contributes.



🌳 2️⃣ Random Forest


Your dataset is sent through hundreds of decision trees (you trained with ~150–200 trees).


Each tree makes a small decision, e.g.:


“If age > 60 → stroke”


“If glucose > 140 and BMI > 28 → stroke”


etc.




Each tree votes, and the final probability = average of votes.


Example: 180 trees vote “stroke”, 20 vote “no stroke”
→ Probability = 180 / 200 = 0.9 (90%)




✅ Good for catching nonlinear relationships (like combinations of factors).

⚡ 3️⃣ XGBoost


Works smarter than Random Forest — it builds trees one-by-one.


Each new tree learns from the mistakes of the previous ones.


If the model previously misclassified older diabetic people → next tree focuses more on that.




Gradually improves until predictions are highly optimized.


✅ Gives the highest accuracy in your evaluation (AUC = 0.92).
✅ Works best for real-world stroke prediction deployment.

🧮 STEP 3: Ensemble Averaging
In your ensemble_predict_proba():
for name, pipe in MODELS.items():
    p = float(pipe.predict_proba(df)[0][1])
    model_probs[name] = p
    total_prob += p

avg_prob = total_prob / len(MODELS)

So, each model gives a probability:
